HEADWORD: Falling
<hw>Fall"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & n.</pos> <def>from
<er>Fall</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Falling away</b></col>, <col><b>Falling
off</b></col></mcol>, etc. <cd>See <cref>To fall away</cref>, <cref>To
fall off</cref>, etc., under <er>Fall</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos></cd> --
<col><b>Falling band</b></col>, <cd>the plain, broad, linen collar
turning down over the doublet, worn in the early part of the 17th
century.</cd> -- <col><b>Falling sickness</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>,
<cd>epilepsy.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Falling star</b></col>.
<fld>(Astron.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Shooting star</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Falling stone</b></col>, <cd>a stone falling through the
atmosphere; a meteorite; an a⟦eum⟧rolite.</cd> -- <col><b>Falling
tide</b></col>, <cd>the ebb tide.</cd> -- <col><b>Falling
weather</b></col>, <cd>a rainy season.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
<au>Bartlett.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

